I have compiled and run this branch on rusty.  I did a run with the quickstart problem \(cube128\) where I restarted after around 2Myr \(40 snapshots\). Similar to Brooke’s results below, I found that the age and relative age sometimes show a high \(~200%\) difference at the star’s first timestep, but that the difference reduces to below a few percent very quickly.  There is no difference in behavior following a restart.  

Here are plots of the percent difference \(as a decimal\) between the relative age and actual age as a function of snapshot since the onset of star formation and as a function of the individual star’s age.  I used Brooke’s equation for the percent difference and followed the convention of black before the restart and red after.  Let me know if you want to see any of the code for making these plots.

![](https://bitbucket.org/repo/8XAGbBb/images/3767606808-image.png){: data-width='50' data-layout='align-start' }
![](https://bitbucket.org/repo/8XAGbBb/images/859381182-image.png){: data-width='50' data-layout='align-start' }
Here is also a plot of relative age vs. age for each star in each snapshot, with the black line indicating the one-to-one line. 

![](https://bitbucket.org/repo/8XAGbBb/images/4109052818-image.png){: data-width='50' data-layout='align-start' }
I also did a run with my usual initial conditions \(similar to the Jets methods paper\) and found generally similar results although I have only a few snapshots for that test. Let me know if I should post the results from that test run, but I think the cube128 results above are sufficient to demonstrate that this pull request is good to go.

I approve this pull request!

This runs on Trillium within ~80 minutes with the timestep fix, and reproduces the correct D-type and R-type solutions at the resolution chosen for the test. I approve this pull request!

